statement.tex:
\\ \textbf{Picking a line-of-attack}
%text

Which of the following will make it \underline\text{easier} 
to solve the integral? 
%

options.tex:
\begin{align}
I &= \int\frac{x^2}{1+x^3}\cdot dx = \int\frac{(x^2-1) + 1}{(1+x^3)}\cdot dx  \\
&= \int\frac{\overbrace{(x-1)\cdot (x+1)}^{x^2-1}}
{\underbrace{(x+1)\cdot(x^2-x+1)}_{a^3 + b^3 = (a+b)\cdot (a^2-ab + b^2)}}\cdot dx + \int\frac{dx}{x^3 + 1} \\
&= \int \frac{(x-1)}{x^2-x+1}\cdot dx + \int\frac{dx}{1+x^3}
\end{align}

reason.tex:
%text
\underline\text{Always try the simplest thing first}.

In this case, notice that $\frac{d}{dx}(x^3 + C) = 3x^2$.
Hence, \underline\text{if we let $z = 1+x^3$}, then 

%
\begin{align}
\frac{dz}{dx} &= 3x^2 \implies x^2\cdot dx = \frac{dz}{3} \\
\therefore I &= \int\frac{x^2\cdot dx}{1+x^3} = \frac{1}{3}\int\frac{dz}{z}
\end{align}
